<common-name datatype='string'>ymdA</common-name>
<comment datatype='string'>The activity of the &lt;i&gt;ymdA&lt;/i&gt; promoter was increased after cold shock exposure [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28582517&quot;&gt;Kim17a&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
The &lt;i&gt;ymdA&lt;/i&gt; transcript is present during the exponential growth phase [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28582517&quot;&gt;Kim17a&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
The probable &lt;i&gt;ymdAB-clsC&lt;/i&gt; polycistronic transcript was detected only after cold shock exposure [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28582517&quot;&gt;Kim17a&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
Overexpression of &lt;i&gt;ymdA&lt;/i&gt; inhibited biofilm formation and increased the susceptibility to apramycin. These effects were dependent on the presence of the &lt;i&gt;sucA&lt;/i&gt; gene. On the other hand, biofilm formation increased in &lt;i&gt;ymdA&lt;/i&gt; knockout cells compared with wild-type cells. This effect was even greater in &lt;i&gt;ymdA-ymdB-clsC&lt;/i&gt; triple knockout cells [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28582517&quot;&gt;Kim17a&lt;/a&gt;].</comment>
